<paragraph blockId="37.[138,1185,1319,1439]" pageId="37" pageNumber="2955">
This species and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hood" authorityYear="1918" box="[344,451,1319,1343]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Haplothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="2955" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="varius">
<emphasis box="[344,451,1319,1343]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="2955">H. varius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are both associated with the flowers of 
<taxonomicName box="[927,1106,1319,1343]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="37" pageNumber="2955" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Amaranthaceae</taxonomicName>
in the arid zone, but the setal lengths are strikingly different in the available samples, as indicated in the key. It is smaller than 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bagnall" authorityYear="1918" box="[477,603,1383,1407]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Haplothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="2955" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robustus">
<emphasis box="[477,603,1383,1407]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="2955">H. robustus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with the major setae much smaller and the male genitalia distinctive. The larvae are bright red.
</paragraph>
